{"author":{"id":"df79d9acb56ef89cd944cc8548377a5d54d09f0704d032bd86e5f202c0cd02f7"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1535537730,"nonce":"/4udhOSOaF1HEbIppWpUj7AQWuQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNjkwMTU5MA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/2054#issuecomment-416901590"},"message":"If we restricted ourselves to only OSI approved licenses, a lot of problems go away. I am sympathetic to this goal. Popular but not open source tools could still be in the tool shed of course, but perhaps restricting iuc-tools in this way is too idealistic?\n\nRelated to this, I assume everything the IUC is accepting nowadays has a conda package, which means the underlying tool is sufficiently openly licensed to allow for packaging, redistribution and automated installation.\n\n(See e.g. https://github.com/bioconda/bioconda-recipes/issues/6456 where Pear was originally available like that, but was later put under new terms and this was no longer possible).\n\nIf so, we're talking about if we should accept tools which can be packaged and installed - but come with usage restrictions (like no commercial use without buying a license).\n\nOn an aside, should the Tool Shed be exposing the license information of dependencies more explicitly - especially anything not OSI approved?","files":null}]}